snippet.textDisplay:
so the transmission should be checked when the oil is warm, engine running and in neutral, if its a Allison you're in luck, they make one of the most reliable auto boxes going, if its the 3000 series it should take 18.5 litres of ATF. id recommend changing the filters when you can they suffer with solenoid failure. oil oil will wreck them, if its a ZF or VOITH box then when you service it be sure to check for the hidden torque converter bung when draining, if you don't do this you're essentially only change half the oil. having said that I'm pretty sure you've got a allison box.
the button on the fuel filter is the fuel primer, when changing the fuel filers, fill both filters up with diesel then put those suckers up, and start priming, if you have problems, keep pumping and turn the engine over it'll fire right up. as a time served HGV mechanic I'm excited to see what you guys do to this.

and that starting fluid is like spraying brake cleaner into the air filter it'll get anything going. :)

snippet.textDisplay: Boys...you don't have a footbrake...you have foot valve...and air brakes......120 psi is the max, and you would get a a buzz alarm when too low...around 80 to 100 lbs...fanning the brakes down, andall the air brake tests must be followed. You need to look up how to test them before you go on the road, and an air endorsement perhaps....Don't hit the foot valve when your red air brake plug is "ON" ....the air brake release valve....brakes applied mode.....looked like you pulled it to release the brakes....fun times
